DoorDash / RBC Complimentary DashPass Terms

Complimentary DashPass from DoorDash- RBC Royal Bank
By clicking “Activate Free DashPass”, you acknowledge that you have received, 
read, understood and agree to all of the Complimentary DashPass Subscription 
offer terms and conditions (“Offer Terms”). The Offer Terms take effect at the 
time you click the “Activate Free DashPass” button, in the Province or 
Territory in which you live.
How to Receive a Complimentary DashPass for Eligible RBC Cardholders?
To receive a complimentary DashPass subscription you must subscribe to 
DashPass with an Eligible RBC Credit Card by i) clicking on “Add RBC Card”, the 
offer located on the home screen of your DoorDash account, or the offer that 
pops up when you add an Eligible RBC Credit Card to your DoorDash account, or 
on “Account” and select “Get $0 delivery fees with DashPass”, and ii) accept 
the DoorDash terms and conditions, and activate your benefit by clicking 
“Activate Free DashPass” before July 5, 2023 (“Offer Period”). If you are an 
existing DashPass subscriber and have already added an Eligible RBC Credit Card 
to your account you must i) either click the offer located on the home screen 
of your DoorDash account or on “Account” and select “Manage DashPass” and ii) 
accept the DoorDash terms and conditions, and activate your benefit by clicking 
“Activate Free DashPass” during the Offer Period. If you have been charged for 
DashPass you will receive a refund to the method of original payment, in the 
amount of the monthly subscription fee for the month you activate your 
complimentary subscription. For all clients, by clicking on “Activate Free 
DashPass” you agree to the DoorDash Terms and Conditions which can be found 
here.
Eligible RBC Credit cardholders include primary cardholders, co-applicants, 
authorized users, primary business cardholders and secondary business 
cardholders on an eligible RBC Credit Card account.
The DashPass monthly subscription fee will be waived (“Complimentary DashPass 
Subscription”) and you will receive either a 3 month or 12 month Complimentary 
DashPass Subscription based on the Eligible RBC Credit Card you use to 
subscribe to DashPass.
DashPass subscriptions purchased through third parties, including third-party 
payment accounts, or online or mobile digital wallets (like Apple Pay and 
Google Pay) are not eligible for the Complimentary DashPass Subscription.


12 Month Complimentary DashPass Subscription:
As an RBC® Avion® Visa Platinum‡, RBC® Avion® Visa Infinite‡ , RBC® Avion® 
Visa Infinite Privilege‡, RBC® Avion® Visa Infinite Privilege‡ for Private 
Banking, WestJet RBC® World Elite Mastercard‡, RBC Rewards® Visa‡ Preferred, 
RBC® Cash Back Preferred World Elite Mastercard‡, RBC® Cathay Pacific Visa‡ 
Platinum, RBC® British Airways Visa Infinite‡, RBC® Avion® Visa Business‡, RBC® 
Avion® Visa Infinite Business‡ cardholder, you are eligible for a Complimentary 
DashPass Subscription for 12 months from the date you subscribe to receive the 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription. You will be auto-enrolled into full-price 
membership at the then-current rate after the end of the 12 month Complimentary 
DashPass Subscription. Your RBC credit card account must be open and not in 
default to maintain the benefits of DashPass.
3 Month Complimentary DashPass Subscription:
As an RBC Rewards+TM Visa‡, Signature® RBC Rewards® Visa‡, RBC® Visa‡ 
Platinum, RBC® Visa‡ Cash Back, RBC® Cash Back Mastercard‡, RBC® Visa‡ Classic 
Low Rate Option, RBC® Visa‡ Classic, RBC® Student Visa‡ Classic, RBC® Visa‡ 
Classic II Student, RBC® Visa‡ Gold, RBC® U.S. Dollar Visa‡ Gold, RBC Rewards 
Visa‡ Gold, RBC RateAdvantage® Visa‡, WestJet RBC® Mastercard‡, RBC® Visa‡ 
Business, RBC® Visa‡ Business Gold, RBC® Visa‡ CreditLine for Small BusinessTM, 
or RBC® Business Cash Back Mastercard‡ cardholder you are eligible for a 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription for 3 months from the date you subscribed 
to the Complimentary DashPass Subscription. You will be auto-enrolled into 
full-price membership at the then-current rate after the end of the 3 month 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription. Your Eligible RBC Credit Card account must 
be open and not in default to maintain the benefits of DashPass.
Your Eligible RBC Credit Card may only be used with one DoorDash account to 
receive a Complimentary DashPass Subscription. Once you have received a 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription you cannot use the same eligible RBC Credit 
Card to obtain a Complimentary DashPass Subscription with another DoorDash 
account.
You are only eligible for one 12 month Complimentary DashPass Subscription and 
one 3 month Complimentary DashPass Subscription during the Offer Period. The 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription commences on the date you subscribe to 
receive the Complimentary DashPass Subscription. For example, if you subscribe 
to a 12 month Complimentary DashPass Subscription on the last day of your 
second month of a 3 month Complimentary DashPass Subscription you will receive 
a total of 14 months of Complimentary DashPass Subscription.
In order to validate your credit card as an Eligible RBC Credit Card, Royal 
Bank may need to administer a $0.50 charge to validate your card enrollment. 
This charge will be reversed in 3 to 5 days once your account has been 
validated.


How to Receive the DashPass Benefits?
Benefits of DashPass from DoorDash include $0 delivery fees and reduced 
service fees on orders from DashPass eligible restaurants that meet the minimum 
order requirement (“DashPass Benefits”). Additional fees on orders may apply. 
For complete DoorDash Terms and Conditions click here. Current price of the 
DashPass subscription is $9.99 CDN per month for all consumers in Canada. 
DashPass orders may be subject to delivery driver and geographic availability. 
Subscription must be activated with a Canadian address.
Once you have enrolled to receive a Complimentary DashPass Subscription, you 
must use an Eligible RBC Credit Card to pay for your DoorDash order to receive 
the DashPass Benefits. If you unsubscribe from DashPass, use a non-RBC Credit 
Card or non-Eligible RBC Credit Card for your DoorDash purchase you will no 
longer be eligible for the DashPass Benefits.
Royal Bank does not act on behalf of DoorDash. DoorDash not Royal Bank is 
responsible for (i) services and products provided through DoorDash; (ii) 
DashPass, including the DashPass Benefits, the administration of DashPass and 
(iii) the DoorDash terms and conditions.
DoorDash does not act on behalf of Royal Bank. Royal Bank is solely 
responsible for (i) the services and benefits offered through Royal Bank and 
(ii) the RBC Agreements.
How to Cancel my DashPass Subscription?
You can cancel your DashPass subscription at any time using the DoorDash app 
or website. Eligible RBC Credit cardholders who enroll and receive a 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription will be automatically enrolled in a paid 
DashPass subscription at the end of the benefit period. Billing for the 
DashPass benefit will commence the next calendar day after expiry date of your 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription. To avoid being charged for the next 
subscription period, you must cancel your DashPass subscription by 11:59pm PST 
the calendar day before the next-scheduled subscription renewal date (e.g. if 
renewal date is January 10, you must cancel by 11:59:59pm PT on January 9). 
After canceling, your DashPass Benefits will be valid through the end of the 
current billing period. Please click here for full DashPass Terms and 
Conditions.
If you re-enroll during the Offer Period using the Eligible Credit Card used 
to activate the Complimentary DashPass Subscription, the length of your 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription will still commence from the original date 
of enrolment, and end 3 months or 12 months after the initial enrolment date, 
depending on which benefit your enrolled card is eligible for.
Changes to the Complimentary DashPass Subscription for Eligible RBC Credit 
Cardholders
The Offer Terms may be changed, cancelled or withdrawn at any time without 
notice to you. Either Royal Bank or DoorDash may, at its discretion, cancel 
your Complimentary DashPass Subscription, including if and when you are or 
become ineligible for the Complimentary DashPass Subscription or if and when 
either of us suspects fraudulent activity.
Notwithstanding any other section of the Offer Terms, the posting of the 
current version of the Offer Terms 
(https://www.rbcroyalbank.com/credit-cards/documentation/pdf/full-doordash-tcs-en.pdf) 
is deemed notice to you of the Offer Terms, where notice is required or 
permitted to be given hereunder. The Offer Terms replace all prior terms and 
conditions with respect to the Complimentary DashPass Subscription offer.
These Offer Terms are in addition to the terms and conditions of any RBC 
Agreements as well as the DoorDash terms and conditions. If there is a conflict 
between (i) the Offer Terms and (ii) the RBC Agreements or the DoorDash Terms 
and Conditions, these Offer Terms will prevail to the extent necessary to 
resolve the conflict.
System Errors
You will receive the Complimentary DashPass Subscription immediately upon 
activating. Should you experience any issues with your Complimentary DashPass 
subscription, please visit DoorDash Support here. A client must notify DoorDash 
of any errors within 30 days of the issue occurring.
Royal Bank is not responsible for any offers missed during the period when an 
error occurs.
Privacy
Royal Bank and DoorDash, and their respective employees, agents and service 
providers, may collect, use and share your personal information from time to 
time for the purposes of enrolment and administration of Complimentary DashPass 
Subscription and provision of the benefits, services that you earn with the 
Complimentary DashPass Subscription. Personal information may include 
information about the first 6 digits of your RBC Credit Card number, the last 4 
digits of your RBC Credit Card number, credit card expiry date and postal code. 
The DoorDash DashPass Privacy Policy is available here. Royal Bank and DoorDash 
may communicate with you about your participation in, or promote and provide 
information about the benefits, services and rewards of, the Royal Bank and 
DoorDash.
Contact Royal Bank or DoorDash
You may contact Royal Bank of Canada at any time by calling our Advice Centre 
at 1-800-769-2512. If you have any questions related to DoorDash or DashPass, 
please contact 1-855-973-1040. Royal Bank of Canada and DoorDash Technologies

Every day Google works hard to keep you and your private information safe
and secure by preventing unauthorized access to your Google Account with
our built-in security protections. And keeping you safe means having strong
privacy practices across our products that minimize how long we store your
personal files and any data associated with them. We want to protect your
private information and prevent any unauthorized access to your account
even if you’re no longer using our services.

Therefore, we are updating the inactivity period
<https://support.google.com/accounts?p=inactive_account_policy_email> for a
Google Account to two years across all our products and services. This
change starts rolling out today and will apply to any Google Account that’s
been inactive, meaning it has not been signed into or used within a
two-year period. An inactive account and any content in it will be eligible
for deletion from December 1, 2023.

*What this means for you:*

    - These changes do not impact you unless you have been inactive in your
    Google Account for two years or have not used your account to sign in to
    any Google service for over two years.
    - While the changes go into effect today, the earliest we would enforce
    any account deletion would be December 2023.
    - If your account is considered inactive, we will send several reminder
    emails to both you and your recovery emails (if any have been provided)
    before we take any action or delete any account content. These reminder
    emails will go out at least 8 months before any action is taken on your
    account.
    - After a Google Account is deleted, the Gmail address for the deleted
    account cannot be used again when creating a new Google Account.

*How to keep your account active?*

The simplest way to keep a Google Account active is to sign in to the
account at least once every two years. If you have signed in to your Google
Account recently in the past two years, your account is considered active
and will not be deleted.

Other ways to keep your account active include:

    - Reading or sending an email
    - Using Google Drive
    - Watching a YouTube video
    - Sharing a photo
    - Downloading an app
    - Using Google Search
    - Using Sign in with Google to sign in to a third-party app or service

There are some exceptions to this policy. Examples include: a Google
Account with YouTube channels, videos or comments; an account that has a
gift card with a monetary balance; or an account that has a published
application, for example, one that hosts an app on the Google Play store.
Other exceptions to this policy are available here
<https://support.google.com/accounts?p=inactive_account_policy_email>.

Google also offers tools to help manage your Google Account and provide
options to back up your data, including the ability to download your data
using Google Takeout <https://takeout.google.com/>, and allowing you to
plan for what happens to your data if you’re inactive for a specific period
of time with the Inactive Account Manager
<https://support.google.com/accounts/answer/3036546>.

Our priority is to make it as easy as possible for you to keep your account
active, if you want to, and we’ll ensure you have adequate notice before
any account is impacted by this change. So before an account is deleted,
Google will send email notifications to the Google Account and its recovery
email (if one has been provided). You should verify that your recovery email
<https://support.google.com/accounts/answer/7299973> is up to date.

*Learn more*

    - Inactive Google Account Policy
    <https://support.google.com/accounts?p=inactive_account_policy_email>
    - How Google retains data we collect
    <https://policies.google.com/technologies/retention>
    - Updating our inactive account policies
     
<https://blog.google/technology/safety-security/updating-our-inactive-account-policies>

A quick Google search will reveal many 'clone' apps, but after a closer look it becomes clear that the core functionality is
always missing.

For example, most YouTube clones will simply recreate the UI, and if we're lucky, will show us how to perform simple CRUD
operations, e.g. commenting on videos.

But for hosting and serving the videos? The public YouTube video API is reused.

Why?

Well, I explored this recently in my full stack development course [https://neetcode.io/courses?utm_source=email]. We handle video
uploads guarded by an auth layer, as well as async video processing via workers.

A simplified architecture diagram might look like this. And this is just for uploading videos. Consuming videos involves many more
steps.

[https://d3b9kr64nievew.cloudfront.net/clka93sfc00cal80o90mf1g04/clkabrbs30129jt0nmyqddjs3.png]


It's becoming clear.

This is not a project you can complete in a weekend.
This is not a beginner friendly project at all.

If you're interested to learn more, I wrote a short design doc
[https://neetcode.io/courses/lessons/design-youtube?utm_source=design-doc] explaining the key architectural decisions (it's free).
Even though we technically came up with a working solution, there are many limitations that I also describe.

I found that this exercise a lot more useful than just whiteboarding a system design diagram. It forces you to think, and yes,
even make mistakes that you can later correct. Let me know if you'd like to see more of this style of content.

Hi John,

We continually strive to give you clear information about – and control over – 
what you share on Strava and how you can use the platform. This year, we’ve 
made some changes to ourPrivacy Policy 
<https://www.strava.com/legal/privacy?$web_only=true> and Terms of Service 
<https://www.strava.com/legal/terms?$web_only=true>. Here are the highlights 
and what you can expect:

 * More clarity and transparency. We’ve updated our Privacy Policy to provide 
you even more information around how we collect, handle, and share your 
personal information – including data that supports community-driven features 
like Heatmaps, Points of Interest, and Metro. 
 * More privacy for minors. We’ve added default settings for users under 18 
that provide more privacy and protection. For example, their profile and 
location information is now hidden by default. 
 * More control around what you share with advertisers. We’ve never sold your 
information for monetary value, and we still don’t. In addition, you control 
whether your data may be shared with third parties to provide you with targeted 
advertising on other platforms. 
 * More user-friendly terms of service. We’ve made it easier to understand 
what content and conduct is and isn’t allowed on our platform. Check out our new
Acceptable Use Policy <http://strava.com/legal/acceptable_use?$web_only=true> 
to understand how we’re protecting your safety and experience on Strava. 

 Open Strava ▸  <https://www.strava.com?$deep_link=true> 

As always, you can review and adjust your privacy controls 
<https://www.strava.com/settings/privacy?$web_only=true> at any time to make 
sure you're comfortable with what you're sharing. These controls allow you to 
create a private profile, hide activities, adjust your map visibility and more. 
Visit ourPrivacy Center <https://www.strava.com/s/privacy-center?$web_only=true>
 to see all the details in one place.

These new policies will go into effect June 30, 2023. By continuing to use 
Strava on or after that date, you’ll be agreeing to these revisions.

We greatly value your safety and privacy, and thank you for being a part of 
our community.

The Strava Team

 Tip of the Month 
 One more way Evernote can simplify your life. 

Crush your classes with Ivy League-caliber notes! 

Why it's great: The Cornell Notes Template is a favorite among Evernote 
students for the way it speeds up note-taking while organizing it into a 
structure that’s easier to understand later. Even non-students might find it 
helpful! 
How it works: 
1.  Open the Cornell Notes Template 
<https://www.evernote.com/shard/s308/client/snv?noteGuid=2570fdd4-9bba-4f02-b112-af226e883b3b&noteKey=a247d23c60403965eec1193f0f401e09&sn=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.evernote.com%2Fshard%2Fs308%2Fsh%2F2570fdd4-9bba-4f02-b112-af226e883b3b%2Fa247d23c60403965eec1193f0f401e09&title=Cornell%2BNotes%2B%257C%2BCourse%2B___%2B%257C%2BMM%252FDD%252FYYYY&displayMode=template>
 and clickUse template to apply it to a new note. 
2.  Enter the appropriate labels, including the date and class name. 
3.  Take notes as they come to you during your lecture or class discussion. 
4.  At the same time, you can record audio 
<https://help.evernote.com/hc/articles/208314418> in Evernote to supplement 
your note. 
5.  Use the “Questions/Cues” section to reframe facts into questions you can 
answer, or cues that help you remember key information. 
6.  Use the “Essential Question” section to sum it all up with a single 
statement. 
7.  Use the “Summary” section to synthesize the most important information so 
you can easily review it later.
